PARECHOVIRUS INFECTION, CHILDREN - AUSTRALIA: (QUEENSLAND)
**********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 4 Jun 2014
Source: The Courier-Mail [edited]
http://www.couriermail.com.au/news/queensland/eleven-cases-of-new-baby-virus-parechovirus-found-in-queensland/story-fnihsrf2-122694208973


Health authorities will this morning [4 Jun 2014] announce an outbreak of parechovirus infection Queensland infants, with the 1st 11 cases of the virus (to be) reported in the state's history.

Parechovirus commonly causes mild respiratory or gastrointestinal symptoms in babies, such as fever, irritability, a rash and diarrhoea. However, in some young infants, the virus can lead to more serious complications such as hepatitis or encephalitis and can be fatal.

Brisbane parents recently had to have their 5-week-old daughter resuscitated in intensive care when she started having breathing difficulties and seizures as a result of the virus (infection). Queensland Children's Medical Research Institute paediatric infectious diseases director Professor Theo Sloots said the virus "affects the brains of young children, and in severe cases can result in death." Some infected babies recover within a few days. In very young babies, the virus can cause infection in the central nervous system and lead to a sepsis-like illness, which can lead to long-term damage to brain cells. "We don't know what the long term affects are; the virus is newly recognised, and we don't know enough about it," Prof Sloots said. All 11 cases are believed to have been found in babies 6 months and under, with the 1st discovered in an infant in Bundaberg in December [2013].

The virus -- for which there is currently no vaccine -- is spread from person to person through contacts with respiratory droplets, saliva or faeces. Young babies appear to be at a higher risk. Good hygiene is the best protection against the virus, with parents encouraged to wash their hands regularly and ensure their mouth and nose are covered when coughing or sneezing. Nationally, 46 babies have been confirmed positive with parechovirus infections.

"The outbreak is Australia-wide now, and we believe there are at least 4 types of the virus, and we don't know what type is in Queensland compared to other states," Professor Sloots said.

[Byline: Laura Chalmers]

