[Human parechoviruses are members of the family of _Picornaviridae_. Although originally described as echoviruses 22 and 23 within the human enteroviruses group because of their clinical and morphological properties, they have since been shown to be distinct from this and other picornavirus groups in several features of their genome organisation, structure and replication. Human parechoviruses show genetic and antigenic heterogeneity, and a number of distinct HPeV types are known to circulate widely in human populations throughout the world.

Anyone can get infected with parechovirus. Young babies appear to be at risk of more severe disease. Parechovirus infection usually causes mild respiratory or gastrointestinal symptoms; however, occasionally it may lead to more severe symptoms. Some infected babies get quite unwell quickly but typically recover in a few days.

In young babies, the virus can cause infection of the central nervous system and can lead to a neonatal sepsis-like illness. Children under 3 months of age are most likely to develop severe disease, but most recover after a few days with supportive treatment. Most people who get infected with parechovirus do not get sick. Some infected babies get unwell very quickly with fever. In addition to a high fever, there are a range of other signs including a red rash, irritability, diarrhoea, hepatitis or encephalitis.

Parechovirus is usually spread from person to person through contact with respiratory droplets, saliva or faeces from an infected person. Anyone can get infected with parechovirus. Young babies appear to be at risk of more severe disease. There is no vaccine to protect you from parechovirus infection. Good hygiene is the best protection. There is no specific treatment for parechovirus; treatment is supportive only. Parechovirus is not a notifiable condition. - Mod.CP

